   <TextArea id="text_area_rules" editable="false" focusTraversable="false" maxHeight="-Infinity" maxWidth="-Infinity" prefHeight="435.0" prefWidth="355.0" style="-fx-control-inner-background: #666666; -fx-border-width: 0;" text="I. General Concept&#10;&#10;Historic Conquest is a game of territorial strategy and general knowledge. Knowledge is used to build an empire, move armies and conquer nations. The board represents a simplified world where every intellectual achievement translates into a geopolitical advance.&#10;&#10;&#10;II. Basic Mechanics (TTMC adaptation)&#10;&#10;The game is based on self-assessment derived from the TTMC rules (Tu te mets combien).&#10;&#10;The Questions :&#10;&#10;For each question, the player chooses a score from 1 to 4 representing their estimated level of knowledge. A high score yields more benefits than a low score. Once the score is chosen, the player must answer the corresponding question.&#10;&#10;Correct answer: the action is validated.&#10;Incorrect answer: the action is cancelled and the turn passes to the next player.&#10;&#10;&#10;&#10;III. Custom rules: the conquest system&#10;&#10;Board layout and setup :&#10;The world is divided into 4 geographical blocks (Europe, America, Africa, Asia/Oceania), each containing 10 zones. A zone comprises several countries.At the start of the game, each zone is assigned a random theme from four: entertainment, IT, tourism, history. Each player chooses a starting zone of their choice. This zone starts with a power of 4. &#10;&#10;Player Actions&#10;&#10;1) Increasing a zone’s power :&#10;If you control a zone, you can answer a question related to its theme. The level achieved (1 to 4) is added to the zone’s power.  A zone cannot exceed 8 power points.&#10;&#10;2) Moving :&#10;To move around the map, the player must answer a question correctly on the theme of their current zone.&#10;Level 1: move to an adjacent zone (distance 1).&#10;Level 2: move distance 2.&#10;Level 3: move distance 3.&#10;Level 4: move distance 4 or inter-zone jump (to any zone). Inter-zone jumps take 2 turns instead of an immediate move.&#10;When moving, a token is placed on the zone. Until a player has conquered the zone they are in, their token remains there and is vulnerable to attacks from the owner. This token has a power equal to the level of the question answered correctly.&#10;&#10;3) Attacking (zone containing a token)&#10;Capturing a neutral zone : &#10;The zone is unoccupied; the player must pass a question (level 1 to 4) to occupy it. The initial power is equal to the level passed.&#10;Attack (siege): to take an opponent’s zone, the attacker answers questions. Each success reduces the power of the opponent’s zone by the value of the chosen level.&#10;Example: a zone with a power of 6 is subjected to a successful level 4 attack. Its power drops to 2.&#10;Once the enemy’s power has been reduced to 0, if the attacker answers another question correctly, they take possession of the zone.&#10;&#10;4) Defend :&#10;The owner of a zone may attempt to eliminate an enemy token present on their territory. If they succeed in the random roll, the opposing token is eliminated.&#10;&#10;&#10;&#10;IV. Further information&#10;&#10;Alliances :&#10;Alliances are permitted, but limited to half the number of players present (e.g. a maximum of 2 allies in a 4-player game).&#10;&#10;Bonuses and penalties :&#10;A player who answers 3 consecutive questions correctly wins a bonus. Conversely, if they fail 3 consecutive questions, they receive a penalty.&#10;&#10;End-of-game conditions :&#10;The game ends immediately if:&#10;A player (or an alliance) controls more than 50% of the 40 zones (i.e. 21 zones).&#10;All opponents forfeit.Only one player (or alliance) remains on the map." wrapText="true" StackPane.alignment="CENTER">
